<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level READ ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_[scope]_case_agent` CONDITIONAL read access to
    `x_[scope]_case` records inside the scoped application `x_[scope]`. The
    condition restricts read to records where the calling user is the
    currently-assigned agent OR is a member of the currently-assigned group
    ("Assigned only" per AAP Section 0.5.6). This is the READ counterpart to
    the sibling WRITE ACL at ../acl/x_[scope]_case_write_agent_assigned.xml;
    the advanced ACL script body is byte-identical between the two records
    by design, since the same predicate gates both read and write access.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_agent row:
          | Role                  | Create | Read              | Write             | Delete |
          | x_[scope]_case_agent  |  Yes   | Yes Assigned only | Yes Assigned only |  No    |
        This file authors the single "Read = Assigned only" cell. The "Yes"
        Create cell is authored by ../acl/x_[scope]_case_create_agent.xml; the
        "Yes Assigned only" Write cell by
        ../acl/x_[scope]_case_write_agent_assigned.xml; the "No" Delete cell
        is enforced by the deliberate ABSENCE of any
        x_[scope]_case_delete_agent.xml file (ServiceNow record-level ACLs
        are deny-by-default: a role with no granting ACL for an operation
        cannot perform that operation).
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - "Assigned only" definition:
          "Assigned only = cases where assigned_agent = current user OR
           assigned_group contains current user."
        The condition script below encodes this predicate exactly: it returns
        true if and only if (a) current.assigned_agent equals gs.getUserID(),
        OR (b) current.assigned_group is non-null AND the current user is a
        member of that group via the OOB sys_user_grmember join table
        (queried indirectly through gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupSysId)).
        Default-deny: the script returns false if neither condition holds.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
          "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write; case_agent
           cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has full access."
        The middle clause ("case_agent cannot access unassigned cases") is
        the central correctness criterion of THIS file: this ACL must DENY
        read on a case where the agent is neither the assigned_agent nor a
        member of the assigned_group. In ServiceNow, denying read also
        causes the record to be excluded from list views, related lists,
        report results, and dashboard widget rows for the unauthorized
        agent - so a robust read-ACL is the linchpin of the entire
        least-privilege design. The validation is exercised by the
        round-trip-verify procedure (../scripts/round_trip_verify.md) in
        which a demo case_agent attempts to read seeded demo cases that
        are NOT assigned to them - the platform must filter those rows out
        of every surface (list, form, report, dashboard).
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level READ binding for the mid-tier
        scoped role and is one of the two records (alongside the WRITE
        sibling) where the "Assigned only" predicate is realized.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "The 'Assigned only' condition for case_agent is
        encoded in the ACL condition script as a query: assigned_agent =
        current.sys_id OR assigned_group IN current.user_group_membership.
        No global ACLs are touched." The encoding is implemented below as
        a CDATA-wrapped scripted ACL expression on the table-level read
        operation.
      - Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map): The case lifecycle
        is Draft -> Open -> In Progress -> (Pending) -> Resolved -> Closed.
        For an agent to drive a case through these transitions, they must
        first be able to READ the case in the list and on the form. This
        ACL determines the universe of cases the case_agent role sees; the
        sibling WRITE ACL determines which subset of those they can update.
        Together, they ensure agents can only operate on cases they own.

    Why this is the READ counterpart to the WRITE ACL:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6 the case_agent role is granted both Read and
      Write under the same "Assigned only" condition. It would be both
      operationally inconsistent and a usability anti-pattern to allow an
      agent to write a case they cannot read, or read a case they cannot
      otherwise interact with. The two ACLs differ only in:
        - <operation>      "read" (this file)             vs "write"
        - <sys_id>         MD5("x_[scope]_case.read...")  vs MD5("x_[scope]_case.write...")
        - <sys_update_name> *_read_agent_assigned         vs *_write_agent_assigned
      The CDATA script body is byte-identical between the two records by
      design; both encode the same predicate per AAP Section 0.5.6.

    How this ACL composes with field-level ACLs (defense in depth):
      This record grants TABLE-LEVEL read to case_agent for assigned cases.
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6 the case_agent is permitted to READ all fields
      on assigned cases (read scope is per-row, not per-column - the field-
      level ACLs at ../acl/x_[scope]_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
      ../acl/x_[scope]_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml restrict only
      WRITE on those sensitive columns, not read). The net effect when an
      agent loads an assigned case form: every column is visible (subject,
      type, status, priority, description, opened_date, closed_date,
      assigned_group, assigned_agent, requester_name, requester_email,
      pending_reason); the field-level ACLs prevent edits to assigned_group
      / assigned_agent on top of this table-level grant. Read access on
      tasks and parties of those cases is granted by the parallel
      ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml and
      ../acl/x_[scope]_case_party_read_agent_assigned.xml siblings.

    Why <advanced>true</advanced> is REQUIRED (CRITICAL):
      The ServiceNow ACL evaluator only invokes the <script> body when
      <advanced> is true. With <advanced>false</advanced>, the platform
      evaluates only the <condition/> encoded query (which is empty here)
      and the <roles> field, granting read to ANY user holding
      x_[scope]_case_agent regardless of assignment. This would directly
      violate AAP Section 0.5.6 and AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 3 ("case_agent
      cannot access unassigned cases"), reducing the agent role to
      effectively the same read scope as case_manager (Read=All) and
      collapsing the entire least-privilege design. Setting advanced=true
      ensures the "Assigned only" predicate in the CDATA script body is
      actually evaluated for every read attempt - including list-view
      filtering, related-list resolution, report row inclusion, and
      dashboard aggregate scope.

    Why direct field access on `current` (not `getRefRecord()`):
      This is a TABLE-LEVEL ACL on x_[scope]_case, so at evaluation time
      the platform binds `current` to the case row being read. We can
      therefore reference current.assigned_agent and current.assigned_group
      directly. This is in contrast to the parallel
      x_[scope]_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml and
      x_[scope]_case_party_read_agent_assigned.xml ACLs, where `current`
      is a CHILD record (case_task / case_party); those scripts must
      navigate up via current.case.getRefRecord() to reach the parent
      case's assigned_agent / assigned_group. Direct access here is both
      more efficient (no extra GlideRecord fetch) and more idiomatic for
      ServiceNow scoped ACL scripts.

    Why gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupId) (not a manual GlideRecord query):
      The platform-supplied gs.getUser() returns the runtime caller's
      GlideUser object, whose isMemberOf(groupSysIdOrName) method is the
      ServiceNow-idiomatic group-membership probe. It internally consults
      the OOB sys_user_grmember join table and the platform's group
      membership cache; it returns true for direct AND transitive group
      memberships. Using it instead of a manual `new GlideRecord(
      'sys_user_grmember')` query (a) keeps the ACL script terse and
      auditable, (b) leverages the platform's membership cache for sub-
      millisecond evaluation on hot paths (list view rendering, form load,
      every report row), and (c) avoids the failure mode where a custom
      query forgets to filter by `user=` or `group=` and returns false
      positives.

    Edge-case behavior (intentional per AAP):
      - Draft cases (no assigned_group, no assigned_agent): both branches
        of the script return false, and the script-level default-deny
        clause returns false at the bottom. case_agents cannot read Draft
        cases, which is correct per AAP Section 0.5.5 - Draft is a
        pre-assignment status; cases must transition Draft -> Open (with
        assigned_group populated) before agents acquire visibility.
      - Cases with assigned_group set but no assigned_agent: the first
        branch (current.assigned_agent == currentUserId) returns false
        because null does not equal a real user sys_id. The second branch
        runs, and any agent who is a member of the assigned_group can
        read the case. This is correct - it implements the "group-level
        triage" pattern where any group member can pick up unassigned
        case_agent work for their group.
      - Cases with both assigned_group and assigned_agent set, where the
        caller is the assigned_agent: the first branch short-circuits to
        true, skipping the group lookup entirely. This is the hot path
        for an agent's "My open cases" widget (../reports/
        x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml) - those rows always pass on branch 1.
      - admin role: bypasses this ACL entirely via the admin_overrides=true
        attribute below. Platform administrators can always read every
        case in the scope without needing the case_agent role.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section 0.3.2;
    no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/services/
        users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration map
        (`Map&lt;String, List&lt;Object&gt;&gt; rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by
        the property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that model, an
        "agent-equivalent" role would have been associated with privilege
        identifiers such as `acm-case-read` or `acm-case-view`, and the
        per-record "assigned only" check would have been imposed at runtime
        by Spring service classes (e.g., a SecurityFilter calling into
        AcmAssignedObject.getAssignee() and comparing against the
        authenticated principal, plus an additional check against the
        principal's authority list for the assignedGroup). The ServiceNow
        target replaces this bifurcated model (declarative privilege list +
        imperative service check) with a single declarative scoped record-
        level ACL whose scripted condition body carries the identical
        predicate. This XML record is the direct equivalent of the
        (case_agent, READ, ASSIGNED-ONLY) cell in the conceptual ArkCase map.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/com/
        armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        plus a private role-name normalization step that uppercased the
        role, replaced whitespace with underscores, replaced periods with
        double-underscores, and prepended the constant `ROLE_` prefix
        from RolePrivilegesConstants). This entire service surface is
        replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted privilege resolver is
        needed. The role-name-normalization step in particular is
        replaced by the scoped-application convention of using literal
        scope-prefixed role names (e.g., x_[scope]_case_agent) directly
        in the <roles> field below - no `ROLE_` prefix is prepended, no
        case folding occurs, and the role name is treated as an opaque
        identifier resolved by name against the OOB sys_user_role table.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_[scope] scope (sys_scope = x_[scope], sys_package =
        x_[scope]). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_[scope]_case (NOT the OOB `task`
        table or any other global table), and <roles> references the
        scoped role x_[scope]_case_agent.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name /
        source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The CDATA
        script body uses gs.getUserID() (returns the runtime user's
        sys_id, NOT a literal) and current.assigned_agent /
        current.assigned_group field references (resolved by the
        platform at request time, NOT by literal). The <sys_id> below is
        THIS record's own deterministic primary key (MD5 of the canonical
        identifier "x_[scope]_case.read.case_agent.assigned", a stable
        key for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to any other
        record. Computing the sys_id deterministically guarantees the ACL
        is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs and round-trip
        Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_[scope]_case` with NO
        dot. Field-level read restrictions are NOT specified by the AAP
        for the case_agent role - per AAP Section 0.5.6 the agent reads
        the entire row including assigned_group / assigned_agent (those
        columns have their own field-level WRITE ACLs but NO field-level
        READ ACLs). This means a case_agent who passes THIS table-level
        read check sees every column on the assigned case; the field-
        level ACLs only constrain what they can edit.
      - Operation = read: corresponds exactly to the "Read = Yes Assigned
        only" cell in the AAP matrix. The other operations (create, write,
        delete) are authored by separate ACL records or enforced by the
        deliberate absence of granting ACLs (deny-by-default for delete).
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required
        so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or override
        scoped data without needing a case_agent role grant. It does NOT
        widen case_agent privileges - case_agents without admin still see
        exactly what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = true: the script body below IS evaluated at every read
        attempt (see "Why advanced=true is REQUIRED" rationale above).
      - condition (empty): no encoded-query condition is set; the entire
        access predicate lives in the scripted body. ServiceNow ACLs
        evaluate condition AND script (both must permit when both are
        present); leaving condition empty defers all logic to the script.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_[scope]")
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml (resolves <name>x_[scope]_case</name>)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_assigned_agent.xml (the script
          references current.assigned_agent; the column must exist when
          the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_assigned_group.xml (the script
          references current.assigned_group; the column must exist when
          the script body is parsed/registered)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_agent.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_[scope]_case_agent</roles> by role name)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
          (the demo agent's read access during round-trip verification
          depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_*.xml (demo cases are
          inserted by the seed pass; this ACL governs subsequent demo-time
          reads by case_agent in list views, forms, reports, and
          dashboards)
        - ../reports/x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml (the agent-workspace
          "My open cases" report queries x_[scope]_case with the row
          filter assigned_agent = current user; the runtime ACL filter
          is layered on top of that - this ACL is what makes the report
          row scope correct even if a case slips through the report
          filter)
        - ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_[scope]_agent_workspace.xml
          (dashboard widgets aggregate over case rows; ACL filtering
          determines which rows the case_agent's session sees)

    The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved verbatim per AAP
    convention; the Personal Developer Instance auto-assigns the actual
    concrete scope id at App Engine Studio creation time, and the
    Update-Set apply-time renaming propagates consistently across all
    bracketed placeholders in this artifact.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>true</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Table-level ACL: x_[scope]_case_agent can read x_[scope]_case records ONLY when assigned_agent = current user OR assigned_group contains current user (per AAP Section 0.5.6 'Assigned only'). Affects list views, form load, related lists, report rows, and dashboard aggregates - any unauthorized case row is filtered out of every read surface.</description>
        <name>x_[scope]_case</name>
        <operation>read</operation>
        <roles>x_[scope]_case_agent</roles>
        <script><![CDATA[(function() {
    var currentUserId = gs.getUserID();
    if (current.assigned_agent == currentUserId) {
        return true;
    }
    if (current.assigned_group && !current.assigned_group.nil()) {
        var groupId = current.assigned_group.toString();
        if (groupId && gs.getUser().isMemberOf(groupId)) {
            return true;
        }
    }
    return false;
})();]]></script>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>ed26b2ef9256d55de66e4c1ac7b1997e</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_[scope]_case</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_[scope]_case_read_agent_assigned</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>

